The wall drill can teach you how to keep the club behind your body on the downswing, but if it’s not done correctly, you’re trading one fault for another. 

While practicing the drill remember to rotate your left knuckles down and move your right elbow in front of your body. Blending these feels will close the club face and prevent your trail arm from getting stuck. This is how you fix a steep downswing and an open club face the correct way 👊

Not a fan of high tees. I think they band-aid bad habits and/or force you into exaggerated positions to raise the arc, such as tilting away from the target or standing up (early extending) through impact. 

I prefer teaching players to use a lower tee height because it prevents bad habits and forces better fundamentals. It’s hard to trust at first, but you can still shallow and hit up on the ball as long as you control the low point of your swing. This will help you in the long run producing more consistency off the tee

Jon Rahm Swing Analysis

Rahm’s swing is so good in so many ways, I wanted to share a few things I see that may help you understand why he’s so good of the tee and with his irons. 

He keeps his hips back (away from the ball) from setup to impact (see line in the picture). This allows his upper body to “cover the ball”. Golfers that keep their hips back like this are typically excellent iron players. 

Rahm has a very short backswing. This may rob him some power, but he still smashes it so there’s no reason to lengthen the backswing. In fact, lengthening his swing could hurt his swing. If he added more wrist hinge, for example,I doubt his lead wrist would stay that bowed. That’s because it’s harder to keep the wrist flexed the more you hinge. More hinge would open the club face in his backswing and that would open up a can of worms on his downswing. He would have to change everything to match up that backswing. I would keep the short backswing forever! 

His club is laid off at the top. It’s a great position to be in when you have a short backswing, especially when the club face is square from his bowed lead wrist. His shaft is pre-set shallow so he doesn’t have to manipulate the club to shallow it more on the downswing. It’s already there. His top backswing is like other players’ early downswing 😂💯

With a driver, he creates extra side bend through impact, while at the same time maintaining shaft lean at impact (third picture). The side bend shallows his attack angle and the shaft lean reduces his dynamic loft. Side bend and shaft lean paired together produce an extremely low spin loft. This is how you create a ton of efficiency with a driver. 

When he gets aggressive, he pulls down very hard. When you have the shaft already behind you, and you pull straight down without giving yourself time to rotate, you could get the club stuck behind you. In late downswing, the hand path could move out to right field causing “blocks” and “hooks.” 

Bottom line, Rahm, IMO, has the most sustainable swing on tour. And his short game isn’t bad too 🤦‍♂️🏆

@golfwith_q breaking down early extension at our recent staff meeting 👏👏👏 Quinn talked about the root causes of early extension because it’s often a compensation for earlier faults in the swing. Once the root cause is identified, that’s where we use our knowledge and creativity to help our players create lasting changes 👌

Such an interesting practice swing from @mccarthy_denny who’s looking red hot in the 3rd round at the @theplayerschamp.

You can see he’s rehearsing a “fade” feel by exaggerating an out-to-in swing path.  What’s most interesting, however, is that he takes off his right thumb and forefinger. My guess is he’s practicing a “no flip” feel by not using his right hand. If you can swing out-to-in without flipping, you’re going to hit deadly straight short iron shots or a small little fade, which is great for approach shots when you need to generate some spin in order to stop quickly on firm surfaces. Is he’s playing a fade to a left pin? Or is it because it looks like the ball is above his feet? Either way, super cool practice swing. Who’s his coach? I love it 💯 💯💯

I want to share a drill that I commonly use with my students to overcome early extension. Before you get started, make sure to address any underlying issues that contribute to early extension such as an early release with the hands or lack of flexibility. Nevertheless, here’s a drill to practice at the range. Focus on your right heel. Keep the right heel down until your hands get to shoulder height in the follow-through. Next, keep your right heel down until your hands get hip height in follow through. Next, keep your right heel down until impact. Practicing the sequence will teach you how to keep your right heel down so your right hip stays away from the golf ball. This gives your upper body the chance to stay down so you can move your hands ahead of the ball and deliver shaft lean for better contact.

Check out this drill if you early extend (stand up) through impact. 

Place a box (or water bottle) in front of your right foot at setup. Focus on hitting shots without knocking the box over. To do this, you’ll have to learn how to keep space between your right hip and ball as you rotate. This will keep your right heel down longer and make it easier to stay down through impact. 

Improving your early extension is both technical and physical. If you’re not flexible, you’ll struggle rotating your hips independent of your upper body to create the right sequence on the downswing. If your thoracic spine is tight, you’ll struggle bending to the right (for a righty) while you rotate. You’ll have to improve your ability to do these things physically before you try to do them technically. 

Technically, early extension is a symptom of faults made earlier in the swing. One of those faults is an open club face prior to impact. When your clubface is open you’ll use your hands to square the club face on the downswing. This causes the shaft to release early. Since you won’t have any shaft lean at impact you’ll learn to compensate by standing up to prevent a fat shot. Another common fault is a steep shaft early on the downswing because standing up can help shallow the club late on the downswing. But late shallowing comes with a price. You don’t want to rely on big compensations to hit the ball straight!

Stay tuned for more tips on how to prevent early extension.

Congrats to @mattfitz94 on his win at Harbour Town. 

His swing is so unique I thought I’d share some of my thoughts. His style dispels many myths - “fundamentals” that amateurs think they need in their swing. The golf swing is so individualized. You have to learn what makes your pattern work, and stick to it. If you’re really struggling, then change is warranted. 

The patterns in his golf swing are largely the result of how he grips the club with his left hand. It’s very strong and there’s a lot of cup (extension) in his left wrist (slide 2). 

He starts his backswings like you see other players, but then quickly shallows the shaft in the backswing by externally rotating his trail shoulder and pronating his lead forearm. This flattens the shaft angle (the shaft points outside the ball-target line). It also opens the club face, which is the real purpose behind this unique move IMO. I think he’s equalizing his very strong left hand grip, which normally closes the face (slide 3). 

His next move that is unique is increasing the cup in his lead wrist at the top of his swing. This has an opening effect on the club face, which I think is another way he equalizes the strong left hand grip (slide 4). 

If he didn’t do both of those moves, the club face would get extremely shut at impact strictly because of the grip. This is why I think those are important moves in his swing that he shouldn’t change, even if they look like faults. Of course, he may have to monitor them in case they become excessive, but right now it’s working really well, so don’t mess with anything that ain’t broke. 

His cross-handed pitching is very unique but doesn’t surprise me. I think there’s a possibility he used to struggle with pitching because of his strong grip, which is typical for players because a strong grip shuts the face and causes the leading edge to dig into the ground. The cross handed style lowers the lead hand down the shaft and removes some of the cup in his wrist. It doesn’t make his left hand grip so strong. This can help him manage the club face better because the face won’t get so shut and dig the leading edge.

If that red line moved on the other side of the yellow line, @scottie.scheffler would not be on the PGA Tour

Scottie gets a lot of flack for his footwork, but there is functionality behind it. When the feet move further from the ball, it means the legs and hips are keeping their distance from the ball. That gives the arms plenty of space and freedom to swing in front of the body. It’s very common for amateurs to move their legs and hips closer to the ball causing a variety of mistakes due to corrections the body makes to hit the ball solidly, and straight. Learning to maintain the space between the legs/hips and the ball helps you stabilize your posture so you can improve your ball striking. Good luck to Scottie this weekend!!

The legend, Michael Block 

Here are some things I see with his swing:

At the top, he has a good blend of depth and height. The trail shoulder is neutral - doesn't look excessively internal or external. 

His lead wrist is flexed and the trail wrist is extended. These are great wrist positions at the top. 

What I find interesting about the top of the backswing is his club face position. The face angle is open to the lead wrist. Typically, you see players have their club face closed to the lead wrist. Other teachers like to look at the club face relative to the lead arm, but I prefer looking at the club face relative to the lead wrist. 

In transition, he pulls the arms down quickly and externally rotates his trail shoulder. At the same time, he starts to rotate his body and side bend to the right. This causes the club to drop into a very shallow position. 

The club head drops well inside the hands at the shaft parallel, but since he closes the club face early on downswing, and rotates his body well, he’s able to manage the path and face without too much manipulation.

One of the most noticeable aspects of his swing (to my eye), is how he stays in knee flex through impact. His right knee continues to flex through impact because he’s not using the ground (vertical force). You’ll see his body stay very low through impact with his right knee moving toward the loft knee. I typically see this leg action with older golfers that lack strength in the legs and/or mobility in the hips/T spine. This is why he doesn’t create a ton of speed and has a stall and flip. It could create a hook scenario with the club head stuck behind him. 

Just my two cents on his swing ✌️

Overall, I love Blockie!!! I’m a massive fan and can’t wait to see more of him on the PGA Tour. What an inspiration for PGA Professionals!!

Here’s a great example of what appears to be a fault, but is not for this player. 

Look at Collin Morikawa’s right knee kicking toward the ball with his right heel high off the ground. 

This may appear to be a fault, and can be for many amateurs, but it doesn’t cause any issue for Collin because his lead hip is well behind the ball. He’s basically rotating extremely well and keeping his hips back. This allows space for his arms to swing in front of his body freely. That leaves room for the right knee to move toward the ball without taking up too much space. 

For golfers that don’t swing as well @collinmorikawa (which is nearly everyone 😂) your hips probably move closer to the ball, which means you don’t have enough space to kick your right knee toward the ball. Your arms will get jammed and you’ll stand up to create space. This is why some of you, probably most of you, would be better off keeping your right heel closer to the ground. It will keep the trail hip and knee further away from the ball so your arms can swing in front of your body. Don’t forget there’s always exceptions to the rule. This may not be the best advice for everyone, but in my experience, it really helps amateurs improve their ball striking.

Early Extension tip. 🔈up! 

A common fault with amateurs is extending the body prior to impact. A good way to correct this swing fault is improving how the legs and hips shift and rotate, and specifically, not allowing the trail knee (right knee for a righty) to move too close to the ball at impact. 

In my previous post, I talked about @collin_morikawa , and how his right knee moves close to the ball.  This does not influence his ball in striking in a negative way because he rotates so well and keeps his lower body away from the golf ball. Look at my previous post, specifically where his left hip is at impact. It’s very far from the golf ball. This allows space for the right knee to move toward the ball so he can stay down and compress the ball. 

But you don’t move like Morikawa! Your lead hip probability does not move away from the ball as good as he does, so your right knee should not move too close to the ball. If you practice the drill I mention in the video, it can help you learn how to shift and rotate and give you space to stay down and compress the ball 🔑🔑👊

Listen up if you’re trying to shallow the club but struggle changing your wrist angles, arm structure, external rotation, etc. Here are a couple ideas for you:

The first is understanding the importance of turning in your backswing and creating depth. This helps you attack from the inside even if you have a slightly steepening move with the shaft on the downswing. Lack of turn minimizes depth, which typically causes the hand path and shaft to move steeply back to the ball. 

The second is tilting away from the target. This will help you easily drop the hands and club to the inside. Tilting toward the target will easily result in an OUT movement of the hands in transition and a steep shaft, causing a “down and across” impact (not good for woods!). 

Hope this helps 👊

If you’re struggling with your swing, don’t forget to look at your set up. You may find the setup was causing the inconsistency, not the swing! 

This video is about a lesson I recently gave a lesson where the student was hooking the ball because his grip was too strong, and he had the ball position too far forward. Both combined, it gave the face too much opportunity to close. The corrections were a weaker grip with the ball position further back (less forward). It changed everything and he was hitting it great. Don’t overlook the setup!

Sometimes players get too shallow and struggle with blocks and hooks, fat and thin misses. I often see this when golfers move their head away from the target in the backswing and/or slide their hips on the downswing. When this happens, the club drops behind them and gets “stuck” from the inside. The path becomes too inside-out causing pushes if the face is square to the path, or hooks if the face is closed to the path. The club also lowers to the ground early which can cause a fat shot or a thin shot. 

The focus for this type of pattern should be not tilting away from the target in the backswing and/or downswing. That will (likely) produce a neutral path and a better attack angle. Remember to think about the opposite when you work on this. Sometimes it’s the only way to make a change!

I worked with a player recently who was scooping at impact. He released the club too early causing fat and thin shots, lack of compression, and a very high ball flight. 

I walked him through a sequence of drills to get him a better feel for a new impact position. If this is something you struggle with, save this video! I’ve had a lot of success teaching this to golfers that struggle with this fault.

This is a common mistake I see from my students. They grip the club so strong with the right wrist flexed (bowed). It reinforces a flexed trail wrist position at impact the scoop and struggle with fat and then Mrs.. When they had driver, their ball flight is super high with tons of spin. Listen up to what I helped them work on to improve! Hopefully this is helpful to those of you who struggle with the same faults 👊

Across the line at the top is a common fault. This is where the shaft points to the right (for a righty) at the top of the swing. Some players can play consistently with this position. but for many golfers I work with it causes major faults at impact. Listen up if across the line is causing big mistakes in your game! 

The product I’m using is @watsongolf theHANGER. This is by far one of the best tools in the game to overcome common faults in the swing. Check it out!

There are many ways to swing a golf club, and do it well. 

Look at @dustinjohnsongolf. He has a strong grip and a flexed (bowed) lead wrist - both of which close the club face. He matches that up with less forearm rotation (lead forearm supination) on the downswing. If he supinated his lead forearm, FORE left! 

Look at @justinprose99. He has a weak grip and an extended (cupped) lead wrist - both of which open the club face. He matches that up with more forearm rotation (lead forearm supination) on the downswing. If he didn’t supinate his lead forearm, FORE right! 

Take a look at your swing. How is your grip and what does your lead wrist look like at the top. This is a good place to look when developing a plan to improve your swing 👌

If you don't appreciate what the hands are doing in the golf swing, you're missing the whole picture.

This was a lesson I recently taught. He was struggling with missing to the right with his driver. 

He was practicing a flat left wrist at the top, but was still struggling missing to the right. That's because his wrist was cupping in transition. That means the face was opening in transition, not a good recipe for consistency. 

In the “after” swing, he was able to maintain the position in transition and began to see a much better result. 

If you struggle with missing shots to the right, you may not need to flex your wrist more in the backswing. It could be that you are cupping in transition. You will need feedback from video or a teacher, but don’t overlook these subtleties.

@nellykorda posted this video of her practicing putting. I thought it was interesting to see where her eyes were positioned at setup in relation to the ball. Most people practice with their eyes over the ball, which I think works really well, but her eyes are slightly inside the ball. It also looks like her shoulders are closed to the start line, but I think that’s only because the camera is close. Her shoulders look super level at address (there’s zero tilt, or only a little). This is much easier when the lead hand is low. Always interesting to see the best players practice their fundamentals. Nelly’s stroke is solid!!🏆
